data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Problem on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (no abort = no exception) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerThread = new Thread(ProcessLoop);
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop()
    {
        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(_cts.Token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit naturally.
                // If you want to continue processing remaining items instead of
                // exiting, simply `continue` here (equivalent to the old
                // ResetAbort behavior that kept the thread alive).
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish its current work item
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after the grace period, the thread is stuck in
        // uncooperative code. There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in
        // modern .NET. See "Uncooperative code" below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

### 1. `volatile bool _running` → `CancellationToken`
The token is thread-safe by design and can also **unblock waiting calls** — a `volatile bool` cannot.

### 2. `Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`
Cooperative cancellation. The worker must check the token — it won't be forcibly interrupted.

### 3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`
The `when` filter ensures you only catch cancellations you initiated, not unrelated ones.

### 4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed
Not needed. After catching `OperationCanceledException`, execution continues normally. Use `continue` if you want to keep looping (old `ResetAbort` behavior) or let the loop condition exit.

### 5. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(timeout)`
`Join` actually waits for the thread to finish rather than blindly sleeping.

### 6. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token
This is **critical**. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it must accept the `CancellationToken` so it can wake up:

```csharp
// Before — blocks forever, can't be cancelled
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection<T>
}

// After — unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

## ⚠️ Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing the token to blocking calls** | `_cts.Cancel()` only works if the blocked code checks it. Without this, `Stop()` hangs indefinitely. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it where you have specific cleanup. Let it propagate everywhere else. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running. |
| **Uncooperative code (no token support)** | If `GetNextItem()` calls third-party code you can't modify, there is **no .NET 8 equivalent to `Thread.Abort`**. Move the work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` as a last resort. |
